<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-420-392  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 420 392.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 10 1989 v23 n28 p68(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Survey: narrow IS security view. (information systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Moran, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The '1989 Ernst andamp; Whinney Computer security Survey Report'concludes that most US corporations have a short-sighted view ofinformation systems security.andP;  Although 84 percent of thosesurveyed said that information security is important, only 39percent had implemented continuity planning.andP;  Security tends to betreated as a data processing issue and not a business issue.andP;  TheErnst andamp; Whinney report concluded that data processing departmentsare not equipped to handle the new security environment created bydistributed computing, networking and interconnectivity.andP;  Networksecurity was regarded by only 17 percent of the corporations assignificant and just five percent said that they use secret codesfor confidential data in public networks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ernst and Whinney (surveys).andO;Topic:     SecuritySurveyInformation Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>